<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 94 / Briefcase, Q&amp;A: Proxies that really mean nothing
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
As I cannot attend the annual general meetings of companies in which I have
an investment, I have always completed and returned the proxy voting forms
authorising the 'chairman of the meeting' to vote according to the wishes I
express.
In view of the article by David Wighton, 'Power of the shareholder' (FT,
April 9), it would appear that a proxy vote will be used only when those
present at the meeting demand a poll.
If this is correct, it would seem that such a vote would be of little use
except where matters of contention arise.
You are correct to say that proxy votes are used only when a show of hands
proves indecisive or goes against the resolution.
But you could always authorise a proxy, other than the chairman of the
meeting, to vote according to your wishes. (Answer by Murray Johnstone
Personal Asset Management).
