<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 94 / UK Company News: 3i's net assets improve 39% to Pounds
1.85bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
3i's results, issued with the pathfinder prospectus yesterday, revealed a 39
per cent increase in net assets to Pounds 1.85bn.
The figure demonstrated the improvement in the health of the unquoted
companies in 3i's portfolio, said Mr Ewen Macpherson, chief executive.
The results for the year to end-March 1994 were flattered by the release of
a Pounds 152m provision for deferred tax on unrealised appreciation, which
will no longer be needed because 3i will have exemption from capital gains
tax once it floats as an investment trust. Without this write-back, net
assets increased by 27.7 per cent and a 30.3 per cent return on
shareholders' funds.
3i's total return - from all forms of interest fees and capital gains - was
Pounds 555m, compared with Pounds 88m the previous year. By far the largest
element of this increase came from the Pounds 210m increase in the
unrealised value of the portfolio.
3i said the growth in value of the portfolio resulted from an 'improvement
in the profitability of underlying investee businesses, certain investments
being valued in excess of their costs for the first time and higher price
earnings multiples of comparable listed companies'.
Of this, about Pounds 100m referred to investments being valued in excess of
cost for the first time. Another Pounds 101m of the increase in total return
was the result of a sharp decrease in provisions - from Pounds 170.9m to
Pounds 38.8m - and an increase in profits on investments realised during the
year. Revenue profits before tax increased by 24 per cent to Pounds 65.4m.
The group is paying the seven banks and the Bank of England, which together
own 3i, a dividend of Pounds 37.6m, up from Pounds 26.8m.
As part of the flotation, 3i is restructuring via a tax-efficient rights
issue and special dividend to existing shareholders. The group will pay a
special Pounds 290m dividend which will be funded from a rights issue to the
existing shareholders that will raise exactly the same amount.
</TEXT>
