<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 94 / UK Company News: NatWest interest in TSB Bank purchase
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
National Westminster Bank said yesterday that it had expressed interest in
buying TSB Bank, the fifth biggest Irish bank. TSB trustees have discussed a
merger with National Irish Bank, a subsidiary of National Australia Bank.
NatWest is thought likely to have to bid more than Pounds 100m for TSB if an
offer was allowed. Lord Alexander, NatWest's chairman, has personally told
the Irish government that his bank would like to be allowed to bid for TSB
Bank.
NatWest said that it believed that it could reinforce its presence in
Ireland by buying TSB. It already owns the third largest Irish bank in
Ulster Bank, which is significantly smaller than Allied Irish Bank and Bank
of Ireland.
National Australia Bank has said that it is in discussions with the TSB
trustees and the Irish government over merging its subsidiary National Irish
Bank with TSB.
</TEXT>
