<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 94 / Madrid prosecutor quits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Spain replaced its chief public prosecutor yesterday in the latest in a
series of high-level resignations over the last four weeks. The departure of
the controversial Mr Eligio Hernandez was not directly related to recent
corruption cases. However, his impartiality had been called into question by
opposition parties. A government spokesman denied that the move was
connected to a forthcoming Supreme Court decision on Mr Hernandez's
qualifications for the job, and said Mr Hernandez was leaving at his own
request, submitted a fortnight ago.
Professional legal associations challenged his appointment in 1992 on the
grounds that he did not fulfil the criterion of 15 years' experience in the
judiciary. The cabinet named Mr Carlos Granados, a Supreme Court judge, to
replace him.
