<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 94 / Spanish pay rises low
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Spain's escalating labour costs are being sharply reduced as unions settle
for below-inflation salary increases in the 1994 round of collective wage
agreements. An annual pay increase over the next two years of 2.75 per cent
covering 150,000 bank employees, which was signed yesterday, followed an
agreement with unions for a 2.5 per cent wage rise in the construction
industry. Year-on-year headline inflation is currently 4.9 per cent and is
expected to fall to 3.5-4 per cent by the end of this year.
Mr Ignacio Montejo, chief economist at Madrid brokers FG, forecasts that
average wage increases through Spain this year will be within the 2-3 per
cent range and that unit labour costs will rise by 1.5 per cent against an
increase of 3 per cent in 1993. For most of the past decade Spain's unit
labour costs rose between 5 and 8 per cent a year.
