<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 94 / Conference on stability skips Balkan problems
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN and ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The European Union yesterday got its new 'conference on stability' in
eastern Europe and the Baltics under way, at the price of setting aside
contentious Balkan issues, including disputes between Greece and Albania and
Italy and Slovenia. Two regional round tables dealing with central European
and Baltic issues would be convened 'at the earliest opportunity' by the EU,
as part of 'a new impetus' agreed by the foreign ministers and officials
from more than 40 participating countries, whose aim is to settle ethnic and
border disputes before the former communist states enter the Union.
The general consensus was reached despite rumbling disagreements. Mr Andrei
Kozyrev, Russia's foreign minister, said Russia, which sees itself as the
protector of the rights of ethnic Russians, was awaiting full details of the
composition and scope of the Baltic round table before deciding. Slovenia,
which aspires to EU membership, was struck off the list of full participants
at the insistence of the new Italian government. Rome's refusal to discuss
border issues with its Slav neighbours was criticised by Mr Lojze Peterle,
Slovenia's foreign minister, but he agreed to continue bilateral talks. At
the closing session Albania's foreign minister, Mr Alfred Serreqi, attacked
the Greek government for 'dangerous and unacceptable manipulation' of the
Greek minority in Albania. But Mr Theodoros Pangalos, Greece's European
affairs minister, used his position as EU president and conference chairman
to overrule the Albanian complaint.
</TEXT>
