<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow nudged lower by Philip
Morris
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stocks were mixed yesterday but a big loss by Philip Morris nudged the
bellwether blue chip index into negative territory, writes Frank McGurty in
New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 1.84 lower at 3,753.46, while the
more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was a scant 0.72 better at 457.06.
Advancing issues led declines by 1,170 to 891 on moderate volume of 255m
shares.
In the secondary markets, the American SE composite added 0.37 to 439.62,
while the Nasdaq composite eased 0.43 to 731.64.
Activity was listless as investors began to square their positions ahead of
the three-day Memorial Day weekend.
The market had only a shred of economic news to guide sentiment. The Labor
Department said that initial claims for state unemployment benefit had
receded by 1,000 last week, against an expected decline of 7,000. The
figures, combined with an upward revision of the total number receiving
jobless benefit, suggested that the labour market was weakening a bit. But
the data was not viewed as compelling evidence of an economic slowdown.
The bond market, meanwhile, offered neither an obstacle nor a source of
encouragement for stocks. Treasury prices were little changed. A flurry of
buying that followed the release of the jobless numbers soon gave way to
profit-taking on the heels of the previous session's late rally.
Among the Dow components, Philip Morris stood as the only impediment to
further improvement by the index, which had followed bonds to a modest gain
during the previous session. On Wednesday, trading in Philip Morris was
halted for the entire session, an unusual move which coincided with a
day-long meeting of the company's board.
During the conference, the directors had considered a proposal to split the
company's tobacco and food businesses into separate entities. After the
markets closed, Philip Morris announced that it had rejected such a move
'for the foreseeable future'.
When the stock resumed trading after a brief delay yesterday morning, it was
quickly marked down Dollars 3 1/8 to Dollars 50 5/8 amid disappointment over
the board's decision. Breaking the company up has been suggested as a way to
limit the financial impact of future tobacco-related lawsuits.
The stock's downturn partially offset a big gain by Boeing. The aerospace
group's share price jumped Dollars 2 1/2 to Dollars 46 7/8 on news that it
was nearing completion of a Dollars 5bn deal to deliver more than 50
commercial aircraft to China.
Upjohn climbed steadily during the afternoon amid speculation that the
company would become a takeover target. The stock closed Dollars 3 3/4
higher at Dollars 32 7/8 .
Deere shed Dollars 2 1/4 in heavy trading even though AG Edwards issued a
'buy' recommendation on the issue.
After Wednesday's burst of activity, technology stocks were relatively
quiet. Computer Associates International, however, surged Dollars 6 1/8 to
Dollars 43 1/4 in volume of nearly 4m shares. The software company beat
analysts' forecasts by posting fourth-quarter net income of 93 cents a
share.
Elsewhere, Compaq gave back Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 117 5/8 after a Dollars
3 gain the previous session.
On the Nasdaq, Lotus Development dropped a further Dollars 2 to Dollars 61,
after reaffirming its initial second-quarter earnings estimates of between
42 and 50 cents a share.
Canada
Toronto ended mixed in moderate trade, the TSE 300 Composite index rising
39.34, or 0.92per cent, to 4330.71 in volume of 59.3m shares.
Twelve of the 14 stock groups increased, with transportation stocks
recording the day's biggest rise of 5.55 per cent. Mining and industrial
products were up 1.42 per cent and 1.39 per cent respectively. Consumer
products added 1.24 per cent. Golds were moderately lower.
Toronto-Dominion Bank gained CDollars  5/8 to CDollars 22 1/8 after
reporting much higher second-quarter earnings.
Mexico
Equities closed lower for the first time in seven sessions because of profit
taking and Wall Street's slight decline.
The IPC index closed off 16.71 points at 2,455.45, a loss of 0.68 per cent.
Volume totalled a moderate 1.2bn new pesos on 109.1m shares traded.
Brazil
Sao Paulo fluctuated widely but ended the day almost flat on profit-taking.
The Bovespa index rose 404 points, or 1.8 per cent but only 0.5 per cent in
real terms.
</TEXT>
