FT  27 MAY 94 / International Company News: Burma fund planned by HK group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Kerry Securities, the Hong Kong-based securities group, is to launch an
investment fund focusing on Burma, Reuter reports from Hong Kong.
It hopes to raise USDollars 50m to Dollars 100m through Myanmar (Burma)
Fund, a closed-end, direct investment fund, according to Mr Richard Neville,
director of corporate finance.
A total of 20m shares, targeted at institutional investors, will be issued
initially at Dollars 10 each. The minimum subscription is Dollars 100,000.
The fund will be launched in the first week of July and remain open
throughout the month.
It will be domiciled in the Channel Islands and a listing will be sought in
Dublin. Kerry Investment Management will manage the fund. Irrawaddy
Advisors, a private non-governmental agency, will be investment adviser.
The fund will investing initially in tourism-related projects,
infrastructure and industrial parks in Burma. Its key strategy would be
co-investments with domestic entrepreneurs or overseas Myanmar or Chinese
business groups.
Kerry Financial Services is controlled by Malaysian tycoon Mr Robert Kuok
and Malayan United Industries.
