<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 94 / International Company News: BCI share price hit by L2,362bn
issue plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Banca Commerciale Italiana, the recently-privatised Italian bank,
fell by 4.4 per cent yesterday on news that the bank wants to raise up to
L2,362bn (Dollars 1.5bn) through an issue of new shares and warrants.
Although the proposal will not be approved by the bank's directors until
June 1, the company decided to make a statement late on Wednesday because of
increasing market speculation about an increase in capital.
According to the statement, the board will also consider plans to seek
shareholder authorisation for further capital increases of up to L2,000bn
over the next five years, through the issue of bonds.
BCI yesterday declined to comment on the reasons for the planned capital
increases, but some of the funds could be used to help strengthen
cross-shareholdings with other European banks.
Earlier this week, the Italian bank announced it was negotiating to buy a 1
per cent stake in Commerzbank of Germany, which already has a stake in BCI
and a seat on the board.
BCI is also part of the consortium which yesterday proposed buying a large
stake in Creditanstalt of Austria. Creditanstalt is represented on the board
of BCI and has been a shareholder since the Italian bank's foundation last
century.
Yesterday, BCI shares fell from L5,341 to L5,105. If the plan is approved,
BCI will issue 525m new shares on the basis of one new share for each pair
already held, at a price of L3,000 a share. A further 262.5m shares will be
issued for the exercise of warrants, convertible into shares at the same
price.
BCI was controlled by IRI, the Italian state holding company, until its
privatisation in March. Since then, Mr Romano Prodi, IRI chairman, has
expressed his disappointment that a few large institutions gained control of
both BCI and Credito Italiano, the other newly-privatised bank.
</TEXT>
