<DATE>940527
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 94 / International Company News: Austrian consortium bids for
Creditanstalt stake
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ZURICH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The struggle to privatise Creditanstalt-Bankverein, Austria's second-largest
bank, moved into a decisive phase yesterday as a consortium of leading
Austrian financial and industrial companies offered Sch7.2bn (Dollars 622m)
for just over half of the government's 70 per cent voting stake in the bank.
The consortium came together in recent weeks to counter a bid by the Swiss
CS Holding financial group that had the apparent support of Mr Ferdinand
Lacina, the Socialist finance minister.
Mr Lacina has argued that Creditanstalt needs a strong strategic partner.
But politicians and business leaders close to the conservative Austrian
People's Party have reacted angrily to the prospect that the bank that once
bestrode an empire fall into foreign hands.
Mrs Maria Schaumayer, the widely-respected president of the Austrian
National Bank, said in an interview last week that Creditanstalt 'must sail
under the Austrian flag, not the Swiss one'.
The consortium is led by EA-Generali, the insurance group and First
Austrian, a large Vienna savings bank, and includes 18 blue chip industrial
companies, such as Brau-Union, Porsche, Radex, Swarovski and Constantia, as
well as some unidentified private individuals.
The consortium immediately nailed its nationalist colours to the mast,
stating that the presence of several domestic companies 'would guarantee an
essentially Austrian underpinning for the bank's further development'.
It argued that in the light of the increasing openness of the Austrian
economy and the country's plan to join the European Union, 'the presence of
an Austrian bank in the whole of Europe, both in the EU and in eastern
Europe, is necessary'.
The consortium would buy more than half of the government's Creditanstalt
shares at the current market price of about Sch675, and would undertake to
place the rest in financial markets 'as soon as possible'.
Socialists snicker that the 'so-called Austrian consortium' contains several
non-Austrian owned companies, including Generali and Banca Commerciale
Italiana of Italy and the Austrian subsidiary of Siemens and Commerzbank of
Germany.
Terms of the CS offer have not been revealed, but Mr Rainer Gut, chairman of
the group built around Credit Suisse, said in an interview with an Austrian
magazine last week that CS would buy a 20 to 30 per cent stake as a first
step and insist on first refusal on further sales of the finance ministry's
holding. Ideally, Mr Gut said, CS would ultimately want to hold 100 per
cent.
He said Creditanstalt under CS control would retain its own identity but
follow CS strategies. It would also benefit from CS strength in
international financial markets.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Creditanstalt-Bankverein.
    CS Holding.
    EA-Generali.
    Die Erste Oesterreichische Spar Casse.
</CO>
<XX>
