<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 94 / Trafalgar omits interim dividend
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Trafalgar House fell by almost 10 per cent yesterday after the
UK-based group reported lower than expected interim profits and said margins
would stay under severe pressure in its core engineering business.
Trafalgar's shares closed 9p lower at 86p although the group, whose
interests range from engineering, construction and property to London's Ritz
Hotel and the Cunard liners, reported that it had moved back into profit. It
omitted the interim dividend.
The group posted pre-tax profits of Pounds 13.4m in the six months to March
31, compared with a Pounds 98.6m loss a year ago when the group made
substantial write-downs in the value of its property portfolio. Turnover was
almost unchanged at Pounds 1.78bn.
Operating profits in the engineering division fell to Pounds 13.1m (Pounds
18.1m) on turnover which slipped to Pounds 1.09bn (Pounds 1.13bn).
Mr Simon Keswick, chairman, said: 'Economic conditions throughout the world,
whilst slowly improving, remain very competitive, particularly in the
engineering and construction industries, and we do not expect any
significant change in the near term.'
Mr Keswick, also chairman of Hongkong Land Holdings, which holds a 25.3 per
cent stake in Trafalgar, added: 'Against this background we are continuing
our efforts to improve the underlying competitive positions of our
businesses. Achieving a return to profit in the half year, albeit a modest
one, is a first step, following the reconstruction of the group's finances.'
Earnings per share were 0.4p, compared with a loss of 18.2p.
Details, Page 20
