<HEADLINE>
FT  27 MAY 94 / Ifil plans issue to pay for expansion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Ifil, the Italian industrial holding company indirectly controlled by the
Agnelli family, is to raise at least L800bn (Pounds 334m) with a complex
share and bond issue to fund expansion in the retailing and agro-food
busi-ness.
Ifil's board also approved yesterday an investment of about L400bn in
convertible bonds, which will give the holding company a 10-year option to
buy a controlling stake in Unicem, the Agnellis' cement business.
The 50.4 per cent stake currently belongs to Ifil's parent company Ifi, and
the operation prepares the way for a reshuffling of Agnelli interests which
would leave Ifil with most of the family's main industrial activities,
except Fiat, the automotive group.
Mr Umberto Agnelli, chairman of Ifil and deputy chairman and chief executive
of Ifi, said yesterday that the operation had a dual purpose: 'On the one
hand it confirms our interest in development opportunities in our own
country, on the other it accelerates the clarification of the holding
companies' role.'
He added that Ifi would remain the financial holding company, with a 'direct
and indirect institutional presence' in Fiat.
Ifil's holdings include a stake in Gruppo Rinascente, the Italian stores
chain, which is one of the potential buyers of Italy's state-owned retailing
and restaurant interests.
The group's consolidated net profits rose to L231.2bn from L192.8bn in 1993,
the company announced yesterday.
